{"overview":"This C-minor sonata movement exhibits a textbook yet dramatically charged sonata form, distinguished by a recurring Grave introduction that irrupts twice into the Allegro trajectory—once at the exposition repeat boundary and once in the coda—creating a structural dialogue between two tempos and affective worlds. The harmonic language is predominantly diatonic with purposeful voice-leading chromaticism (viio7/V, chromatic passing motion in the closing theme), a development that traverses a descending chain of minor thirds (e minor → a minor → g minor) before a dominant pedal reclaims C minor, and a recapitulation that notably darkens the secondary theme by transposing it into the tonic minor.","cross_piece_tags":["sonata_form","dramatic","tragic","pedal_point","circle_of_fifths","chromatic_mediant","counterpoint","meditative"]}
